:::: {.columns}

::: {.column width="50%"}
Research Question

Identify which [predictors]{style="color:purple;"} (spatial, structural, and/or socio-economic) contribute to the most accurate model for the City's Automated Valuation Model
:::

::: {.column width="50%"}
Motivation

Residential property tax assessments have [equitable and financial]{style="color:purple;"} implications for homeowners as well as [fiscal]{style="color:purple;"} implications for the city
:::

::::


![](midterm_presentation_files/Skyline.jpg){fig-align="center" width=100%}


## Data Sources

- [Property Sales]{style="color:purple;"} (Philadelphia, 2023-2024): City of Philadelphia - OpenDataPhilly
- [Socio-Economics]{style="color:purple;"}: United States Census - American Community Survey 
- [Spatial Features]{style="color:purple;"}: City of Philadelphia - OpenDataPhilly

::: {.columns}
::: {.column width="50%"}
![](midterm_presentation_files/Census.png){fig-align="left" width=100%}
:::

::: {.column width="50%"}
![](midterm_presentation_files/CityofPhiladelphiaLogo.jpg){fig-align="right" width=100%}
:::
:::


## Spatial Distribution of Sale Prices in Philadelphia

::: {.columns}
::: {.column width="80%"}
![](midterm_presentation_files/salepricemap.png){fig-align="center" width=80%}
:::

::: {.column width="20%"}
- Higher sale prices are concentrated in [Central]{style="color:purple;"} and [Northeast]{style="color:purple;"} Philadelphia
:::
:::

## Factors Impacting Sale Price

::: {.columns}
::: {.column width="80%"}
![](midterm_presentation_files/TLAbig.jpg){fig-align="center" width=80%}
:::

::: {.column width="20%"}
- There is a notable relationship between [sale price]{style="color:purple;"} and [total livable area]{style="color:purple;"}
:::
:::

## Model Comparison
| Model | RMSE | MAE | R² |
|:------|----------:|---------:|---------:|
| Model 1 | 230,140.41 | 15,174.13 | 0.287 |
| Model 2 | 215,430.39 | 90,217.97 | 0.380 |
| Model 3 | 211,021.39 | 90,144.74 | 0.405 |
| Model 4 | 196,081.17 | 1,582.45 | 0.490 |

: Model Performance Metrics {.striped .hover tbl-left}

- Model 1 (Structural) and Model 2 (Structural + Census) had the worst performance.
- Spatial features (Model 3) and interaction terms (Model 4) boosted model performance.

## Top Predictors 
::: {.columns}
::: {.column width="80%"}
![](midterm_presentation_files/TLAbig.jpg){fig-align="center" width=80%}
:::

::: {.column width="20%"}
- In a wealthy neighborhood ($\beta$ = 47,309.230, p \< 0.01)
- Number of bedrooms ($\beta$ = 35,121.540, p \< 0.01)
- Number of bathrooms ($\beta$ = 25,942.210, p \< 0.01)
:::
:::

## Model Performance

::: {.columns}

::: {.column width="80%"}
![](midterm_presentation_files/Final_Model_CV_Scatter.png){fig-align="center" width=80%}
:::

::: {.column width="20%"}
- Final RMSE: $195,093.2
- MAE: $71,587.66
- The scatterplot shows actual vs predicted values for Model 4 after a 10-fold Cross Validation
:::
:::

## Hardest to Predict 
::: {.columns}
::: {.column width="80%"}
![](midterm_presentation_files/TLAbig.jpg){fig-align="center" width=80%}
:::

::: {.column width="20%"}
- (Enter visualization of residuals by neighborhood)
:::
:::

## Recommendations  
::: {.columns}
::: {.column width="80%"}
:::

::: {.column width="20%" style="text-align:left;"}
- Policymakers should be aware that houses in lower-income neighborhoods will not be accurately predicted by this model
- Physical features of a structure such as the number of bedrooms/bathrooms serve as strong predictors of home sale price. Nearby attractive amenities such as proximity to transit stations as well as distance from crime also contribute.
:::
:::

## Limitations & Next Steps  
::: {.columns}
::: {.column width="80%"}
![](midterm_presentation_files/TLAbig.jpg){fig-align="center" width=80%}
:::

::: {.column width="20%" style="text-align:left;"}
**Limitations**

- Philadelphia sale prices don't have a linear relationship, particularly among lower-priced homes
- Variables used were aggregated and not weighted
:::
:::

## Questions?  
::: {.columns}
::: {.column width="80%"}
:::

::: {.column width="20%" style="text-align:left;"}
**Thank you!** <br>
<br>
Contact us at: *inquiries@tnc.com*
:::
:::

